{
  "response": "# Modal Dialog with Form Validation Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.  \n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA  \n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users, keyboard-only users, low vision users, voice control users, cognitive accessibility users  \n> **Assistive technologies:** JAWS, NVDA, VoiceOver, keyboard-only navigation\n\n**Feature:** Reusable Next.js modal dialog containing a form with real-time and submit-time validation, async validation support, success messaging, and nested modal support.  \n**Risk Level:** High  \n**Component/Page Type:** Modal Dialog + Form Validation + Dynamic Status Messaging\n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\nThis plan covers a reusable modal dialog component with flexible form content. The modal darkens the background, traps keyboard focus, supports Escape/cancel/close dismissal, restores focus to the opener, validates form fields in real time and on submit, announces errors and success states, and supports stacked or nested modals.\n\nThis is a high-risk accessibility feature because it combines three patterns that often fail independently: modal focus management, form error association, and dynamic announcements. The plan assumes WCAG 2.2 AA, with support for NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver, and keyboard-only users.\n\nWhat this plan is claiming:\n- The modal must follow the APG Modal Dialog pattern.\n- Form fields must use native labels and programmatic error association.\n- Dynamic validation must avoid noisy, repeated live region announcements.\n- Nested modal behavior must have a defined focus stack.\n\nWhat this plan is not claiming:\n- It does not prescribe visual branding or exact component API.\n- It does not require every validation keystroke to be announced immediately.\n- It does not assume all forms have the same fields.\n- It does not replace post-implementation screen reader testing.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\nThe modal should be rendered in a top-level overlay layer, but DOM order and focus behavior must remain coherent. The background page should become inert while the modal is open so keyboard users and screen readers cannot interact with obscured content.\n\nThe modal itself uses the APG Modal Dialog pattern:\n\n- `role=\"dialog\"` identifies the modal container as a dialog.\n- `aria-modal=\"true\"` communicates that content outside the dialog is unavailable.\n- `aria-labelledby` references the visible modal title.\n- `aria-describedby` may reference short introductory guidance, but should not point to large form content.\n- The form inside the dialog uses native `<form>`, visible `<label>` elements, and `<fieldset>/<legend>` where fields are grouped.\n\nWCAG grounding:\n- WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships: semantic relationships between dialog title, form groups, labels, hints, and errors.\n- WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order: focus moves into the modal and stays within the current dialog context.\n- WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value: dialog role, accessible name, form control names, and state attributes are programmatically available.\n\n### Structure Diagram\n\n```html\n<body>\n  <a href=\"#main-content\">Skip to main content</a>\n\n  <main id=\"main-content\">\n    <button id=\"open-dialog-button\">Open form</button>\n    <!-- page content -->\n  </main>\n\n  <div id=\"modal-layer\">\n    <div\n      role=\"dialog\"\n      aria-modal=\"true\"\n      aria-labelledby=\"modal-title\"\n      aria-describedby=\"modal-description\"\n    >\n      <button aria-label=\"Close dialog\">\n        <span aria-hidden=\"true\">X</span>\n      </button>\n\n      <h2 id=\"modal-title\">[Modal title]</h2>\n      <p id=\"modal-description\">[Brief form guidance]</p>\n\n      <form novalidate>\n        <div role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\">\n          <!-- non-urgent validation/status messages -->\n        </div>\n\n        <div role=\"alert\" aria-live=\"assertive\" aria-atomic=\"true\">\n          <!-- submit failure summary only -->\n        </div>\n\n        <fieldset>\n          <legend>[Group name]</legend>\n\n          <label for=\"field-1\">[Field label]</label>\n          <input\n            id=\"field-1\"\n            aria-describedby=\"field-1-hint field-1-error\"\n            aria-invalid=\"false\"\n          />\n          <p id=\"field-1-hint\">[Helpful instruction]</p>\n          <p id=\"field-1-error\">[Error message when present]</p>\n        </fieldset>\n\n        <button type=\"submit\">Submit</button>\n        <button type=\"button\">Cancel</button>\n      </form>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</body>\n```\n\nThe `X` icon is decorative because the button already has an accessible name. The icon must be hidden with `aria-hidden=\"true\"` per WCAG 1.1.1 and 4.1.2.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n### Primary APG Pattern\n\n**Modal Dialog**  \nAPG reference: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/\n\nThe modal must behave as a true modal dialog:\n- Focus moves into the dialog when it opens.\n- Focus remains trapped inside the topmost dialog.\n- Escape closes the topmost dismissible dialog.\n- Focus returns to the element that opened the dialog when it closes.\n- Background content is inert and unavailable to keyboard and screen reader users.\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard Model | ARIA Attributes | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Modal container | APG Modal Dialog | Receives managed focus context; does not itself need to be tabbable unless no focusable child exists | `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"`, `aria-labelledby`, optional `aria-describedby` | 1.3.1, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Close button | APG Button | Tab focuses; Enter/Space activates; closes dialog | Native button; `aria-label=\"Close dialog\"`; icon `aria-hidden=\"true\"` | 2.1.1, 2.5.8, 4.1.2 |\n| Cancel button | APG Button | Tab focuses; Enter/Space activates; closes dialog | Native button | 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Submit button | APG Button / native form submit | Tab focuses; Enter/Space activates; Enter in text input may submit form | Native submit button; disabled state uses `disabled` where truly unavailable | 2.1.1, 3.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Text inputs | Native form controls | Tab focuses; typing edits; Enter may submit depending field type | Native label association; `aria-invalid`; `aria-describedby` | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2 |\n| Field groups | Native form grouping | Tab enters controls inside group; no custom key model | `<fieldset>` and `<legend>` | 1.3.1, 2.4.6 |\n| Error summary | Status/alert pattern, not interactive unless links are included | If links are present, Tab reaches each error link; Enter moves focus to field | `role=\"alert\"` for submit failure summary; links point to invalid fields | 3.3.1, 3.3.3, 4.1.3 |\n| Success message | Status message | Does not steal focus unless replacing the form with confirmation state | `role=\"status\"` or focusable confirmation heading depending flow | 2.4.3, 4.1.3 |\n| Nested modal trigger | APG Button opening APG Modal Dialog | Enter/Space opens child modal; focus moves into child | Child dialog gets its own `role=\"dialog\"` and focus trap | 2.1.1, 2.1.2, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n### Opening the modal\n\nWhen the modal opens:\n1. Store a reference to the trigger element.\n2. Make the background page inert.\n3. Move focus into the modal.\n4. Initial focus should go to the first meaningful interactive element, usually the close button or first form input.\n\nFor this component, recommended default:\n- If the form has a short description and the first field is immediately understandable, focus the first input.\n- If the dialog contains important instructions before the form, focus a heading wrapper with `tabindex=\"-1\"` so screen reader users hear the title and context first.\n\nThis satisfies WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order and follows the APG Modal Dialog pattern.\n\n### Focus trap\n\nWhile the modal is open:\n- Tab from the last focusable element wraps to the first focusable element.\n- Shift+Tab from the first focusable element wraps to the last focusable element.\n- Focus must not escape to background page content.\n- The overlay itself should not be inserted into the tab order unless it has a clear interaction.\n- Only the topmost modal in a stacked modal scenario owns the active focus trap.\n\nWCAG citations:\n- WCAG 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap: focus is contained intentionally, and users can exit with Escape, Cancel, Close, or Submit success path.\n- WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order: focus order remains logical.\n- WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value: modal role and state are programmatically exposed.\n\n### Escape key\n\nEscape should close the topmost dismissible modal only.\n\nFor nested modals:\n- Escape in child modal closes child only and restores focus to the child modal trigger.\n- Parent modal remains open and keeps its focus trap.\n- Escape in parent closes parent only after child has closed.\n- Maintain a stack of focus restoration targets.\n\nIf a modal contains unsaved form data, Escape may trigger a confirmation dialog. That confirmation must itself be a modal dialog following the same APG pattern.\n\n### Focus restoration\n\nWhen the modal closes:\n- Restore focus to the element that opened it.\n- If the trigger no longer exists, restore focus to the closest stable logical target, such as the parent section heading with `tabindex=\"-1\"` or a primary action near where the trigger existed.\n- For successful submission that closes the modal, restore focus to the trigger or to a visible success message on the page if the page state changes substantially.\n\nThis satisfies WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n\n### Dynamic validation focus\n\nReal-time validation must not move focus. Moving focus while the user types is disruptive.\n\nOn submit with invalid fields:\n1. Prevent submission.\n2. Render an error summary at the top of the form.\n3. Move focus to the error summary container with `tabindex=\"-1\"` only after submit failure.\n4. Error summary links should move focus to the corresponding invalid field.\n\nThis satisfies:\n- WCAG 3.3.1 Error Identification\n- WCAG 3.3.3 Error Suggestion\n- WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\n### Validation strategy\n\nUse two channels:\n1. Field-level association for all errors using `aria-invalid` and `aria-describedby`.\n2. One shared live region per event class, not one live region per field.\n\nDo not place `role=\"alert\"` on each field error in a repeated template. That creates noisy or duplicated announcements, especially in forms with many fields.\n\nRecommended behavior:\n- On blur: show field-level error visually and associate it programmatically.\n- While typing: update validity state, but avoid announcing every keystroke.\n- On submit: announce a concise error summary assertively and move focus to it.\n- On async validation: announce \u201cChecking [field name]\u201d politely, then announce result only when validation completes.\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual Indicator | Programmatic Indicator | ARIA Attribute | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Modal open | Overlay, dialog visible | Dialog role and modal state | `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Modal title | Visible heading | Dialog named by heading | `aria-labelledby=\"modal-title\"` | 1.3.1, 2.4.6, 4.1.2 |\n| Modal description | Visible guidance text | Dialog described by concise text | `aria-describedby=\"modal-description\"` | 1.3.1, 3.3.2 |\n| Background unavailable | Overlay and dimmed page | Background removed from interaction | `inert` on app root outside modal; optionally `aria-hidden` as fallback | 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Field normal | Default border and no error text | Valid or unvalidated field | `aria-invalid=\"false\"` or absent | 4.1.2 |\n| Field invalid | Error text, icon, red border | Field marked invalid and linked to error | `aria-invalid=\"true\"`, `aria-describedby` includes error id | 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Field hint | Help text below field | Input references hint | `aria-describedby` includes hint id | 1.3.1, 3.3.2 |\n| Async validation pending | Spinner or text \u201cChecking\u2026\u201d | Status announced politely | `role=\"status\"`, `aria-live=\"polite\"`, optional `aria-busy=\"true\"` on form section | 4.1.3 |\n| Submit validation failed | Error summary at top | Assertive announcement and focus target | `role=\"alert\"` for summary, summary container `tabindex=\"-1\"` when focused | 3.3.1, 3.3.3, 4.1.3 |\n| Submit in progress | Disabled submit, loading text | Busy state on form | `aria-busy=\"true\"`; native `disabled` on submit if duplicate submits must be blocked | 4.1.2, 4.1.3 |\n| Submit success | Success message text | Polite or focused confirmation | `role=\"status\"` if staying in modal; focus heading if replacing form | 2.4.3, 4.1.3 |\n| Button disabled | Reduced opacity plus text/state | Native disabled control | `disabled` for native button, not only `aria-disabled` | 4.1.2 |\n| Nested child modal open | Parent visually obscured by child | Only child modal active | Top modal has active trap; parent remains inert relative to child | 2.1.2, 2.4.3 |\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\nColor must never be the only state indicator.\n\nError state:\n- Use red border plus error icon plus visible error text.\n- Error text must explicitly name the problem and suggested fix.\n- The icon is decorative if the text provides meaning, so mark it `aria-hidden=\"true\"`.\n\nSuccess state:\n- Use success text plus icon, not green color alone.\n- Example: \u201cYour changes were saved.\u201d\n\nFocus indicators:\n- Use `:focus-visible`.\n- Use a two-color focus indicator, such as dark outline plus light offset ring, so it remains visible on both light and dark surfaces.\n- Focus indicator must have at least 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors.\n- Account for sticky headers or modal headers so focused fields are not obscured.\n\nTouch targets:\n- Close, Cancel, Submit, and error summary links must be at least 24x24 CSS pixels, with 44x44 recommended.\n- The close icon button must have a visible hit area, not only the icon glyph.\n\nText and zoom:\n- Use relative units.\n- Support 200% zoom without loss of content.\n- Support 400% zoom / 320 CSS px equivalent without horizontal scrolling.\n- Modal should become a full-width or near-full-width sheet on narrow viewports, with internal scrolling only if necessary.\n- Keep modal title and close button visible, but avoid sticky headers that obscure focused form controls.\n\nMotion:\n- Opening/closing animation must respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.\n- No validation animation should be required to understand state.\n- Error appearance must be immediate enough for comprehension without relying on motion.\n\nWCAG citations:\n- WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color\n- WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum\n- WCAG 1.4.4 Resize Text\n- WCAG 1.4.10 Reflow\n- WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast\n- WCAG 2.3.3 Animation from Interactions\n- WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible\n- WCAG 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured\n- WCAG 2.4.13 Focus Appearance\n- WCAG 2.5.8 Target Size Minimum\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n### Dialog content\n\nThe modal title must be visible and specific. Avoid generic titles like \u201cForm\u201d or \u201cDetails.\u201d The title should describe the task, such as \u201cUpdate billing address\u201d or \u201cRequest access.\u201d\n\nThe dialog description should be short. Do not use `aria-describedby` to point to the whole form because screen readers may announce too much content when the dialog opens.\n\n### Form labels\n\nEvery input must have a visible label. Do not use placeholder text as the only label.\n\nPreferred label strategy:\n- Use visible `<label for=\"field-id\">`.\n- Use `aria-describedby` for hints and errors.\n- Use `aria-label` only for icon-only buttons like Close, not for normal form inputs when a visible label can be provided.\n\nWCAG citations:\n- WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- WCAG 2.4.6 Headings and Labels\n- WCAG 3.3.2 Labels or Instructions\n- WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n### Error messages\n\nErrors must be:\n- Specific: \u201cEmail address is missing,\u201d not \u201cInvalid input.\u201d\n- Actionable: \u201cEnter an email address that includes @.\u201d\n- Associated with the field via `aria-describedby`.\n- Reflected with `aria-invalid=\"true\"`.\n\nFor multiple errors:\n- Field-level messages appear near each field.\n- Submit failure renders an error summary before the form fields.\n- Error summary should say how many errors exist and link to each invalid field.\n\n### Success message\n\nIf submission succeeds and the modal remains open:\n- Replace the form with a confirmation region.\n- Move focus to the success heading or announcement container if the user\u2019s task context has changed.\n- Use `role=\"status\"` for non-interruptive success text.\n\nIf submission succeeds and the modal closes:\n- Restore focus to the trigger or move focus to a visible page-level success message if one appears as the new task result.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Automated testing\n\nRun automated accessibility checks for:\n- Dialog accessible name.\n- Valid ARIA attributes.\n- Form labels.\n- Color contrast.\n- Missing or duplicate IDs.\n- Invalid `aria-describedby` references.\n- Hidden focusable content outside the active modal.\n- Error summary links pointing to valid field IDs.\n\nAxe-core will not fully verify focus trap quality, screen reader announcement timing, or whether live region updates are understandable. Those need keyboard and manual screen reader testing.\n\n### Static analysis\n\nFor Next.js:\n- Use JSX accessibility linting as a CI gate.\n- Check invalid ARIA props, missing labels, incorrect interactive nesting, and missing button types.\n- Treat false positives carefully, especially for custom components that forward ARIA props.\n\n### Keyboard test cases\n\n- Tab from trigger, open modal with Enter.\n- Focus moves into modal.\n- Tab cycles through Close, fields, Submit, Cancel, then back to Close.\n- Shift+Tab cycles backward.\n- Focus never reaches background content.\n- Escape closes modal and restores focus to trigger.\n- Cancel closes modal and restores focus to trigger.\n- Close button closes modal and restores focus to trigger.\n- Enter/Space activate Close, Cancel, and Submit.\n- Submit with invalid fields moves focus to error summary.\n- Error summary links move focus to the related field.\n- Async validation does not steal focus.\n- Nested modal opens from parent, traps focus in child, Escape closes child only, focus returns to child trigger.\n\n### Screen reader test cases\n\nTest with NVDA, JAWS, and VoiceOver:\n\n- When opened, dialog title and role are announced.\n- Background content is not reachable while modal is open.\n- Each field announces label, hint, role, value, and invalid state when applicable.\n- Field errors are announced through `aria-describedby`.\n- Real-time validation does not create repeated noisy announcements.\n- Submit failure announces summary once.\n- Success message is announced or focused according to the chosen success flow.\n- Close button announces as \u201cClose dialog, button,\u201d not \u201cX button\u201d or \u201ctimes button.\u201d\n\n### DOM verification\n\nImplementation tests must verify:\n- `role=\"dialog\"` is on the dialog container.\n- `aria-modal=\"true\"` is present only on the active modal.\n- `aria-labelledby` points to the visible title.\n- `aria-describedby` points only to concise guidance.\n- `aria-invalid` lands on the actual form control.\n- `aria-describedby` includes both hint and error IDs when both exist.\n- Error IDs are stable and unique.\n- Background root receives `inert` while modal is active.\n- Only the topmost nested modal is keyboard-active.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Reusable Modal Dialog Shell\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Files:**\n- Modal component\n- Modal focus management utilities\n- Modal tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```html\n<div role=\"dialog\" aria-modal=\"true\" aria-labelledby=\"modal-title\">\n  <button aria-label=\"Close dialog\">\n    <span aria-hidden=\"true\">X</span>\n  </button>\n  <h2 id=\"modal-title\">Dialog title</h2>\n  <div>Dialog content</div>\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `role=\"dialog\"`: exposes dialog role, WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-modal=\"true\"`: communicates modal behavior, WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-labelledby`: gives dialog accessible name, WCAG 1.3.1 and 4.1.2.\n- `aria-describedby`: optional concise description, WCAG 1.3.1.\n- `aria-label` on close button: accessible name for icon-only button, WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on X icon: prevents redundant symbol announcement, WCAG 1.1.1 and 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n- Tab/Shift+Tab trap focus.\n- Escape closes topmost dismissible modal.\n- Enter/Space activate close controls.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Modal has accessible name.\n- Focus moves into modal on open.\n- Focus trap works forward and backward.\n- Escape closes and restores focus.\n- Background content is inert.\n- Nested modal closes topmost modal only.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Form Structure and Field API\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```html\n<form novalidate>\n  <fieldset>\n    <legend>Contact information</legend>\n\n    <label for=\"email\">Email address</label>\n    <input\n      id=\"email\"\n      aria-describedby=\"email-hint email-error\"\n      aria-invalid=\"false\"\n    />\n    <p id=\"email-hint\">Use an address you can access.</p>\n    <p id=\"email-error\">Email address is required.</p>\n  </fieldset>\n</form>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `aria-describedby`: links hints and errors to controls, WCAG 1.3.1 and 3.3.2.\n- `aria-invalid`: communicates invalid state, WCAG 3.3.1 and 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n- Tab moves through fields in visual and DOM order.\n- Enter submits when appropriate.\n- No validation behavior moves focus during typing or blur.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Every input has a visible label.\n- Fieldset groups have legends.\n- Error and hint IDs resolve.\n- Invalid state appears on the input, not a wrapper.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n- 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- 2.4.6 Headings and Labels\n- 3.3.1 Error Identification\n- 3.3.2 Labels or Instructions\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: Validation Messaging\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```html\n<div role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\">\n  Checking email address.\n</div>\n\n<div role=\"alert\" aria-live=\"assertive\" aria-atomic=\"true\">\n  There are 2 errors in the form.\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `role=\"status\"`: polite async validation/status updates, WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `role=\"alert\"`: submit failure summary, WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `aria-atomic=\"true\"`: announces complete status message, WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `aria-busy=\"true\"` on form or field group during async validation, WCAG 4.1.3.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n- Real-time validation does not move focus.\n- Submit failure moves focus to summary.\n- Error summary links focus corresponding invalid fields.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Blur validation associates field error.\n- Typing does not spam assertive announcements.\n- Submit failure announces summary once.\n- Async validation announces pending and complete states politely.\n- Error recovery clears `aria-invalid` and removes error from `aria-describedby`.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n- 3.3.1 Error Identification\n- 3.3.3 Error Suggestion\n- 4.1.3 Status Messages\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: Submission and Success Flow\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```html\n<form aria-busy=\"false\">\n  <button type=\"submit\">Submit</button>\n  <button type=\"button\">Cancel</button>\n</form>\n\n<div role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\">\n  Your submission was successful.\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `aria-busy`: communicates submitting state, WCAG 4.1.3.\n- Native `disabled`: prevents duplicate submit where necessary, WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `role=\"status\"`: success message announcement, WCAG 4.1.3.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n- Submit button activates with Enter/Space.\n- Cancel closes modal and restores focus.\n- Successful submit either focuses confirmation heading or closes modal and restores focus to appropriate post-submit target.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Submit with valid data enters busy state.\n- Submit button prevents duplicate submit accessibly.\n- Success message is announced.\n- Focus behavior after success matches chosen flow.\n- Cancel remains available unless intentionally disabled during critical submit.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- 3.3.4 Error Prevention\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n- 4.1.3 Status Messages\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus Areas |\n|---|---|---|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Modal shell | APG Modal Dialog completeness, focus trap, Escape behavior, focus restoration, background inertness |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 2 | Form structure | Labels, fieldsets, legends, hints, error ID associations |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 3 | Validation messaging | `aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby`, live region strategy, submit error summary |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 4 | Submission flow | Busy state, success messaging, disabled state, final focus destination |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 5 | Nested modal behavior | Topmost trap only, focus stack restoration, Escape handling |\n\n---\n\n## Failure Modes This Plan Prevents\n\n- Dialog opens but screen reader does not hear a title.\n- Focus escapes into the dimmed background.\n- Escape closes the wrong modal in a nested stack.\n- Focus disappears after close because the trigger was not stored.\n- Error text is visible but not associated with the input.\n- Every field error uses `role=\"alert\"` and creates announcement noise.\n- Validation moves focus while the user is typing.\n- Close icon is announced as \u201ctimes\u201d instead of \u201cClose dialog.\u201d\n- Submit failure shows errors visually but does not summarize them.\n- Success message appears silently.\n- Disabled state is only visual.\n- Background content remains tabbable behind the overlay.\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- WAI-ARIA APG Modal Dialog Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/\n- WAI-ARIA APG Button Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/\n- WCAG 2.2 Quick Reference: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/quickref/\n- WAI Forms Tutorial: https://www.w3.org/WAI/tutorials/forms/",
